The central part of one eye is seeing the
hole through the tube.

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:53.240
The central part of the eye other can't see
that because of the tube, and it sees the

00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:55.350
middle of the hand.

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:59.670
And so your brain says, "Well, the central
part of one eye is seeing is the hole.

00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:02.139
The central part of the other eye is seeing
the hand.

00:15:02.139 --> 00:15:06.000
Since corresponding retinal points are seeing
these two different things, they must be in

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:07.300
the same place in space."

00:15:07.300 --> 00:15:09.769
And, you see the hole in the middle of your
hand.

00:15:09.769 --> 00:15:13.160
And, so, that's an example of visual confusion.

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:21.300
Obviously an artificial one, but, it's probably
the most detrimental consequence of strabismus,

00:15:21.300 --> 00:15:24.810
is this overlap of things in visual space.

00:15:24.810 --> 00:15:28.579
Which makes obviously moving through space
very difficult.

00:15:28.579 --> 00:15:29.829
OK?

00:15:29.829 --> 00:15:37.160
And then, of course, the second consequence
of misaligned eyes is double vision.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:41.639
Which some people may have experienced if
they drank a little bit too much.

00:15:41.639 --> 00:15:43.490
Maybe not in this crowd.

00:15:43.490 --> 00:15:46.480
And, let's figure out how double vision works.

00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:48.680
Again, think about the rattle.

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:51.769
Its image is cast on the fovea of one eye.

00:15:51.769 --> 00:15:58.980
But, if the second eye is turned, that image
is now falling on a non-foveal point.

00:15:58.980 --> 00:15:59.980
OK?

00:15:59.980 --> 00:16:03.230
On a different place on the retina of the
other eye.

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:07.699
And so the brain says, " I have two images
of the rattle.

00:16:07.699 --> 00:16:10.660
One from my right and one from my left eye.

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:12.620
They're not falling on corresponding points.

00:16:12.620 --> 00:16:14.790
So, maybe there are two rattles.

00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:19.139
And, they're located in two separate locations
in space."

00:16:19.139 --> 00:16:22.339
And that, of course, is double vision.

00:16:22.339 --> 00:16:23.889
OK.

00:16:23.889 --> 00:16:32.410
So, when I was a child, my strabismus- my
crossed eyes- also called infantile esotropia,

00:16:32.410 --> 00:16:36.250
developed within the first months of life.

00:16:36.250 --> 00:16:41.730
And as a result I adapted fairly rapidly to
the strabismus.

00:16:41.730 --> 00:16:45.509
So, maybe I didnít adapt fairly rapidly,
cause my parents told me a was a really difficult

00:16:45.509 --> 00:16:47.000
infant and toddler.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:53.320
But, I adapted and the way I adapted was to
suppress the input from one eye.

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:58.060
So, I would look with one eye and turn in
the other.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:02.649
And, pay attention to the input from the straight
eye.

00:17:02.649 --> 00:17:06.750
And essentially ignore or suppress the input
from the turned eye.

00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:13.910
And so, I do not remember many incidences
of seeing double as a child or an adult before

00:17:13.910 --> 00:17:16.390
I underwent my vision therapy.

00:17:16.390 --> 00:17:22.750
And, but there are people who develop strabismus
- misaligned eyes- later on in life.

00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:26.730
And maybe plagued with a continual double
vision.

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:29.530
They always see images as double.

00:17:29.530 --> 00:17:32.970
And I was very curious as to what this was
like.

00:17:32.970 --> 00:17:35.880
And I had a student with exactly this situation.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:43.590
And, so, one day over coffee I asked her what-
How it was that she coped.

00:17:43.590 --> 00:17:46.740
And I want to read for you from a section
from my book about what she said.

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:53.110
And, so, it goes like this, "one of my students,
Sarah, developed a form of strabismus when

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:55.370
she was five years old.

00:17:55.370 --> 00:17:59.530
And began to experience constant double vision
in high school.

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:00.820
I wanted to know if she coped.

00:18:00.820 --> 00:18:05.970
So, one day over coffee I asked Sarah what
her view of the world was like.

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:11.870
" She said, " I see two images, but, only
one is real.

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:16.720
I could be driving and seeing two images of
a car, But, I know which one to steer around."

00:18:16.720 --> 00:18:19.289
"This sounded bazaar.

00:18:19.289 --> 00:18:22.610
Not to mention dangerous, so, I asked her
how she knew.

00:18:22.610 --> 00:18:26.440
Sarah thought about this for a moment and
she tried to put into words came automatically

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:27.570
to her.

00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:33.340
Then she said that the car image seemed like
her right eye was in context.

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:37.450
In other words the right eye image of the
car was located relative to other things in

00:18:37.450 --> 00:18:38.450
her surroundings.

00:18:38.450 --> 00:18:42.200
To Sarah, it had a defined location in space.

00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:46.200
She added that in class, she might see two
images of me at the blackboard.

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:50.770
But, again, only the right eye image was real.

00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:51.950
I was curious.

00:18:51.950 --> 00:18:56.600
Does my voice come from the image seen by
the right or left eye.

00:18:56.600 --> 00:19:01.559
Sarah hesitated but said that, the voice came
from the image seen by the right eye.

00:19:01.559 --> 00:19:05.330
If I were to shake hands with you, she added,
I could reach accurately for and shake only

00:19:05.330 --> 00:19:10.470
the hand seen by the right eye."If I tried
to use the left eye image, I'd miss your hand.

00:19:10.470 --> 00:19:15.520
Itís not that I think about this, I just
reach for your hand automatically using the

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:16.830
right eye image."

00:19:16.830 --> 00:19:20.330
"I pointed to the coffee mug in front of her.

00:19:20.330 --> 00:19:25.179
From which of your two coffee cup images does
the delicious coffee aroma come from?"

00:19:25.179 --> 00:19:30.720
"Now that you mention it, she said, It only
comes from the cup image seen by the right

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:31.830
eye."

00:19:31.830 --> 00:19:35.280
So, think about what Sarah had to do.

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:37.270
She had two images of everything.

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:39.490
She has to interact with the world.

00:19:39.490 --> 00:19:43.130
One of those images had to be the interact-able
image with.

00:19:43.130 --> 00:19:47.160
One of those images had to be the one that
she reached for or moved around.

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:48.510
And so on.

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:50.190
And so, she--.

00:19:50.190 --> 00:19:56.740
Her brain unconsciously made a decision about
which of those images was the real image.

00:19:56.740 --> 00:20:01.510
And that was the image that was imbued with
all the other physical characteristics.

00:20:01.510 --> 00:20:03.390
Like the smell coming from the coffee cup.

00:20:03.390 --> 00:20:08.990
Or, the voice coming from me as I was talking
in front of the class.

00:20:08.990 --> 00:20:13.170
And again you might say that real-unreal dichotomy;
that seems pretty bazaar.

00:20:13.170 --> 00:20:15.670
I can't imagine experiencing it.

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:20.090
Well, we can all experience that too, or,
many of us can who have reasonable binocular

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:21.090
vision.

00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:22.090
And here's the trick.

00:20:22.090 --> 00:20:26.850
So, take your hand again, hold up your index
finger, and put it in front of your face.

00:20:26.850 --> 00:20:28.770
But, this time don't look at it.

00:20:28.770 --> 00:20:31.640
Look at me or look further in the distance.

00:20:31.640 --> 00:20:35.400
Can you get a double image of your finger?

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:36.440
OK?

00:20:36.440 --> 00:20:38.430
That's called physiological diplopia.

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:39.550
It's absolutely normal.

00:20:39.550 --> 00:20:41.460
It's because you're fixating further away.

00:20:41.460 --> 00:20:45.620
So, your finger image is falling on disparate
parts of the two retinas.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:46.620
Perfectly normal.

00:20:46.620 --> 00:20:47.620
OK?

00:20:47.620 --> 00:20:52.039
So now, get that double image again and then,
very quickly take your right hand and try

00:20:52.039 --> 00:20:55.270
to grab both of those images.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:58.730
Keep looking in the distance, if you look
at the finger it'll single out.

00:20:58.730 --> 00:21:01.150
So, keep looking in the distance.

00:21:01.150 --> 00:21:02.150
[ pause ]

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:11.390
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: So, I'm seeing a little bit
of this and this, then ,or maybe this over

00:21:11.390 --> 00:21:12.450
here.

00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:14.850
You see what I'm getting at?

00:21:14.850 --> 00:21:18.620
Even though you're not walking around with
continual double vision, when placed with

00:21:18.620 --> 00:21:25.370
the task of grabbing your finger when you
have two images of it, your brain automatically

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:28.240
selected one of those images as real.

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:31.070
One of those images as manipulate-able.

00:21:31.070 --> 00:21:33.270
One of those images is the one you could grasp.

00:21:33.270 --> 00:21:38.640
And, that's the decision that Sarah had to
make on a continual basis.

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:42.130
Until she went to see my optometrist and went
through optometric vision therapy.

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:47.520
And now, her double vision is largely resolved
and she's in Optometry school.

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:54.450
So, anyway, these are some of the consequences
of having crossed eyes.

00:21:54.450 --> 00:22:01.789
And, of course, the third consequence is a
lack of binocular vision, it's a lack of stereo

00:22:01.789 --> 00:22:02.929
vision.

00:22:02.929 --> 00:22:06.970
The ability for example, to enjoy 3D movies.

00:22:06.970 --> 00:22:15.570
I made this slide before "Avatar" and the
big 3D movie phenomenon came along.

00:22:15.570 --> 00:22:20.860
Many of you have probably used " View Masters
" and you have a sense of what I mean when

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:23.650
I say, seeing in 3D.

00:22:23.650 --> 00:22:28.260
I had three operations on my eyes as a child
to make them straighter.

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:32.409
And, although the operations made my eyes
look straighter, it didnít really change

00:22:32.409 --> 00:22:33.670
the way I used them.

00:22:33.670 --> 00:22:36.890
I still continued to look with one eye and
turn in the other.

00:22:36.890 --> 00:22:38.760
It's just now, the eye turn is more subtle.

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:41.230
So, most people didn't notice it.

00:22:41.230 --> 00:22:45.870
But I remember after my third operation being
given a View Master and everyone else in the

00:22:45.870 --> 00:22:48.790
family seemed to enjoy looking into it.

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:50.120
And, I had no idea what they were seeing.

00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:55.200
I mean, Mickey Mouse and Superman looked cute
inside the View Master, but, I didn't really

00:22:55.200 --> 00:22:57.240
understand what it was that they were seeing.

00:22:57.240 --> 00:23:02.520
Because, I still continue to see the image
as flat, because I was really only basically

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:05.090
paying attention to the input from only one
eye.

00:23:05.090 --> 00:23:06.090
OK.

00:23:06.090 --> 00:23:10.789
So, how does stereopsis, or the ability to
see in 3D work?

00:23:10.789 --> 00:23:15.840
Real quickly again, it has to do with the
comparison between the images on the two retinas.

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:22.740
So, letís say your eyes are fixating, are
looking at the point called fix, then its

00:23:22.740 --> 00:23:25.910
image is falling on corresponding retinal
points.

00:23:25.910 --> 00:23:28.890
Now, take a look at target.

00:23:28.890 --> 00:23:34.360
That image is not in the same frontal parallel
plane as fix, but, either somewhere--.

00:23:34.360 --> 00:23:36.120
In this case it's behind it.

00:23:36.120 --> 00:23:42.880
Although we can do an analogous analysis if
it were in front of the point called fix.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:48.809
Follow the dotted lines and look to see where
that image is cast on the two retinas and

00:23:48.809 --> 00:23:53.290
you can see that image is not cast on corresponding
points.

00:23:53.290 --> 00:24:01.549
This distance, "X", is a number of degrees
from the fovea of the left eye that's different

00:24:01.549 --> 00:24:08.230
than this distance, "Y", or angular distance
"Y" number of degrees from the fovea on the

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:09.230
right eye.

00:24:09.230 --> 00:24:12.429
And then, your brain makes new interpretation.

00:24:12.429 --> 00:24:15.670
The two images are falling on non- corresponding
points.

00:24:15.670 --> 00:24:17.940
There's only one image out there.

00:24:17.940 --> 00:24:21.409
It must be in some unique location in space.

00:24:21.409 --> 00:24:27.370
And by dint of how it falls on one retina
relative to the other, it assigns it a place

00:24:27.370 --> 00:24:31.470
in space that's either in front or behind
the other image.

00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:35.790
And, of course that's what happens when you
go to a 3D movie, you're wearing glasses that

00:24:35.790 --> 00:24:41.190
present images seen from slightly different
perspectives as if they were seen from your

00:24:41.190 --> 00:24:42.430
two eyes.

00:24:42.430 --> 00:24:49.080
And your brain then makes that interpretation,
"Oh the image is a little different on the

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:54.049
two retinas and therefore, it's either located
in front or behind the fixation point.î OK?

00:24:54.049 --> 00:24:59.570
So, that's basically how 2D vision works and
obviously if you don't point your two eyes

00:24:59.570 --> 00:25:05.610
at the same place in space, if the eyes are
misaligned, youíre not going to see in 3D.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:13.539
And, operations to fix or try and realign
the eyes may not work.

00:25:13.539 --> 00:25:16.230
Why may they not work?

00:25:16.230 --> 00:25:26.550
Because think about this, think about an infant,
a child by the age of one year has already

00:25:26.550 --> 00:25:30.730
learned how to use their eyes to reach for
things.

00:25:30.730 --> 00:25:34.700
You start reaching for things at about the
age of three or four months of age.

00:25:34.700 --> 00:25:38.990
Which is, incidentally is the same period
of time when infantile esotropia- crossed

00:25:38.990 --> 00:25:41.120
eyes- first develops.

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:42.120
Makes sense.

00:25:42.120 --> 00:25:45.140
If youíre trying to reach for things and
the eyes are not well aligned, you're gonna

00:25:45.140 --> 00:25:47.870
have to do something about it.

00:25:47.870 --> 00:25:52.580
And one thing you could do, maybe your eyes
are just a little bit misaligned, but now

00:25:52.580 --> 00:25:57.429
if you misaligned one of the eyes even more,
cross it in even more, it's even easier to

00:25:57.429 --> 00:25:58.480
ignore its input.

00:25:58.480 --> 00:26:02.830
So, by the time youíre a year old, you know
how to reach for things.

00:26:02.830 --> 00:26:06.970
You have been looking at things from a lying
down position, a sitting position, perhaps

00:26:06.970 --> 00:26:09.580
you're cruising around and walking.

00:26:09.580 --> 00:26:15.000
Your visual habits have become imbedded by
the time you're a year old.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.520
And that's why I think surgery on its own
can't fix the problem.

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:25.720
Because, in order for you to learn how to
use your eyes in a different way.

00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:31.090
That is point them at the same place at the
same point in time.

00:26:31.090 --> 00:26:32.809
You have to be taught.

00:26:32.809 --> 00:26:36.270
This is something you learn naturally within
the first year of life.

00:26:36.270 --> 00:26:40.490
But, after that period of time, if you've
developed different visual habits, you have

00:26:40.490 --> 00:26:43.120
to learn it in a whole new way.

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:44.120
OK?

00:26:44.120 --> 00:26:46.289
So, that's the situation that I was in.

00:26:46.289 --> 00:26:49.779
&gt;&gt; male#4: Why do some people block out second
eye images?

00:26:49.779 --> 00:26:55.440
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Well, actually, I will tell
you an interesting adaption that I used.

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.320
So, when I first-.

00:26:58.320 --> 00:27:01.710
I went to see a developmental optometrist
at the age of 48.

00:27:01.710 --> 00:27:04.159
I didn't go to see her to gain stereo vision.

00:27:04.159 --> 00:27:12.761
The dogma was that if you didnít develop
stereo vision within early childhood, what

00:27:12.761 --> 00:27:17.840
was called the critical period in early childhood,
your brain wired itself up in a way that it

00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:19.080
couldnít rewire.

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.800
And, you were permanently stereo blind.

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:26.500
And, I had read all the papers supporting
this idea.

00:27:26.500 --> 00:27:28.720
And I used to lecture about that in class.

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:33.549
And I used to tell people, " I'm an example
that shows how well this theory of critical

00:27:33.549 --> 00:27:34.549
periods, fits reality".

00:27:34.549 --> 00:27:39.580
I was cross- eyed since infancy, Iím stereo
blind.

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:41.320
OK?

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:49.289
But, what I'm telling you is; you develop
certain adaptations, like you were asking,

00:27:49.289 --> 00:27:50.640
to be able to see.

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:53.330
And, I'll tell you one adaptation I developed.

00:27:53.330 --> 00:27:57.360
I went to see my developmental optometrist
because my gaze was jittery.

00:27:57.360 --> 00:27:58.360
Especially in the distance.

00:27:58.360 --> 00:28:01.399
It was very hard to keep my eyes stable on
anything.

00:28:01.399 --> 00:28:03.549
And, so, that's why I went to see her.

00:28:03.549 --> 00:28:07.769
I really wanted to have more confidence and
competence for driving my children around

00:28:07.769 --> 00:28:08.890
town.

00:28:08.890 --> 00:28:10.580
I found it very difficult to drive.

00:28:10.580 --> 00:28:14.430
Look at a road sign and then go back to the
road, it just was very hard.

00:28:14.430 --> 00:28:15.430
OK?

00:28:15.430 --> 00:28:17.030
That's when I went to see her.

00:28:17.030 --> 00:28:19.539
And she told me how it was that I learned
to read.

00:28:19.539 --> 00:28:23.230
So, I had trouble learning to read in school.

00:28:23.230 --> 00:28:28.460
It took until about fourth grade to catch
up to what other kids were doing.

00:28:28.460 --> 00:28:31.330
And, the way I learned to read was this way.

00:28:31.330 --> 00:28:38.909
When I looked at a book, I would look with
one eye at the letters, and the other eye

00:28:38.909 --> 00:28:43.799
would turn in about fifteen degrees, or, 25
prism diopters.

00:28:43.799 --> 00:28:46.010
Why fifteen degrees?

00:28:46.010 --> 00:28:52.750
Well, if you look at the eye, the image, letís
say the letters, from the eye that was doing

00:28:52.750 --> 00:28:55.659
the reading, fell on the fovea.

00:28:55.659 --> 00:29:03.670
The other eye was turned by fifteen degrees,
so, the image fell on the blind spot.

00:29:03.670 --> 00:29:08.880
On the place where the optic nerve leaves
the retina and goes to the rest of the brain.

00:29:08.880 --> 00:29:13.409
So, in other words, while one eye was looking
at the letters, the other eye did not see

00:29:13.409 --> 00:29:14.590
those letters at all.

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:17.090
Because, the image of those letters fell on
the blind spot.

00:29:17.090 --> 00:29:18.750
What a perfect adaptation.

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:23.779
I can't really claim credit for it . It certainly
wasn't a conscious thing, but, that is eventually

00:29:23.779 --> 00:29:24.899
how I learned to read.

00:29:24.899 --> 00:29:26.820
But, was by making this adaptation.

00:29:26.820 --> 00:29:33.500
And, fifteen degrees is a very common degree
of eye turn for people with strabismus.

00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:34.500
And it makes sense.

00:29:34.500 --> 00:29:39.460
It puts the foveal image of eye on to the
blind spot of the other, a beautiful adaptation.

00:29:39.460 --> 00:29:41.929
&gt;&gt; male#5: It takes away almost the double
vision.

00:29:41.929 --> 00:29:42.929
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: It takes away almost the double
vision.

00:29:42.929 --> 00:29:44.250
Especially for what youíre paying attention
to.

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:45.250
What's on the fovea.

00:29:45.250 --> 00:29:48.059
And, you might say, " well if you can do that
why donít you just put the two images on

00:29:48.059 --> 00:29:49.059
the fovea?"

00:29:49.059 --> 00:29:51.279
But, the blind spot is a much bigger area.

00:29:51.279 --> 00:29:55.080
Much bigger target to aim for than the very
tiny fovea.

00:29:55.080 --> 00:29:56.080
OK?

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:57.080
So-.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:30:00.660
&gt;&gt;male#6: So, I had lateral strabismus when
I was born.

00:30:00.660 --> 00:30:09.500
And I had an operation when I was one or something.

00:30:09.500 --> 00:30:10.500
It was very painless and I donít remember
a thing about it, it went pretty well.

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:11.500
I still have a problem, I don't know if I
have stereovision or not.

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:16.210
I definitely notice sometimes when I'm really
tired.

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:27.039
And, every once in a while something will
click and itís like, um, itís like, uhÖwhen

00:30:27.039 --> 00:30:29.430
I bring the two images together I'll know
it.

00:30:29.430 --> 00:30:32.430
I don't know, it's like the second eye is
aligning.

00:30:32.430 --> 00:30:34.640
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: That's probably what's happening.

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:35.670
Yeah.

00:30:35.670 --> 00:30:39.900
We could- I have some tools you could try
afterwards and see.

00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:42.410
&gt;&gt; male#6: So, Maybe it's gotten better since
then.

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:44.820
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Yeah, well, you can probably
tune it up.

00:30:44.820 --> 00:30:46.809
You can probably tune it up.

00:30:46.809 --> 00:30:51.170
But, yeah, I think your experience of the
double vision, or the eyes looking in, that's

00:30:51.170 --> 00:30:55.639
an example of getting them into better alignment.

00:30:55.639 --> 00:31:00.310
&gt;&gt; male#6: So, why not do the surgery for
infants?

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:01.310
Instead of--

00:31:01.310 --> 00:31:03.320
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Well, the surgery is more
successful if it's done on a child before

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:05.090
the age of one.

00:31:05.090 --> 00:31:09.820
Before, like I said, the visual habits become
entrenched.

00:31:09.820 --> 00:31:15.230
But, it's hard to catch a child at that young
an age.

00:31:15.230 --> 00:31:18.400
And there's risks to doing surgery on a very
young infant.

00:31:18.400 --> 00:31:24.480
And there may be- Those are some of the issues.

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:31.200
And usually surgery alone, if a child does
develop stereopsis, stereo vision afterwards,

00:31:31.200 --> 00:31:34.309
it's not as good as the normal stereo vision.

00:31:34.309 --> 00:31:38.830
So, vision training at the age when they would
have been old enough to do it would still

00:31:38.830 --> 00:31:40.679
probably be recommended.

00:31:40.679 --> 00:31:45.649
But, yeah those are some of the issues out
there.

00:31:45.649 --> 00:31:46.649
OK.

00:31:46.649 --> 00:31:52.019
So then, the question is I've sort of explained
to you the problem.

00:31:52.019 --> 00:31:55.450
And now, I want to give you a little bit of
an idea of the solution.

00:31:55.450 --> 00:31:58.510
How did my optometrist teach me to use my
two eyes together?

00:31:58.510 --> 00:32:01.600
To point at the same place in space at the
same time.

00:32:01.600 --> 00:32:07.019
And to do that, one of the tools that she
used--.

00:32:07.019 --> 00:32:12.179
By the way, she was a developmental optometrist,
which is a small set of optometrists who work

00:32:12.179 --> 00:32:14.320
on this optometric vision therapy.

00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:17.950
Vision therapy to train binocular vision.

00:32:17.950 --> 00:32:22.490
And they're a very rare group of eye doctors.

00:32:22.490 --> 00:32:25.139
To be distinguished from ophthalmologists
who do surgery.

00:32:25.139 --> 00:32:26.139
OK.

00:32:26.139 --> 00:32:29.350
Different types of eye doctors with different
types of expertise.

00:32:29.350 --> 00:32:30.809
OK.

00:32:30.809 --> 00:32:36.100
So, one of the techniques that she used was
developed by my hero.

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:37.950
A man named, Frederick Brock.

00:32:37.950 --> 00:32:41.130
Who passed away in 1971, I never did meet
him.

00:32:41.130 --> 00:32:47.059
But what Frederick Brock understood was that
stereovision, the ability to see with two

00:32:47.059 --> 00:32:50.309
eyes, is not a passive process.

00:32:50.309 --> 00:32:57.630
For most of us, if you have normal binocular
vision, when you look at something close,

00:32:57.630 --> 00:33:00.850
you automatically turn your two eyes in together.

00:33:00.850 --> 00:33:02.690
Make a convergence movement.

00:33:02.690 --> 00:33:08.570
So that the image is close that you want to
fixate, falls on corresponding retinal locations

00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:10.549
on the fovea of both eyes.

00:33:10.549 --> 00:33:14.720
When you then shift your gaze to something
further away, you turn out, or diverge the

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:15.720
eyes.

00:33:15.720 --> 00:33:17.620
These are vergence movements.

00:33:17.620 --> 00:33:21.919
They develop in children within the first
two, four, months of life.

00:33:21.919 --> 00:33:26.899
Or, if youíre like I was, and had infantile
esotropia, they don't develop.

00:33:26.899 --> 00:33:27.899
OK?

00:33:27.899 --> 00:33:30.850
And so, I basically had to learn how to make
vergence movements.

00:33:30.850 --> 00:33:35.669
I had to learn something that most people
learned at two months of age and I learned

00:33:35.669 --> 00:33:37.269
at the age of 48.

00:33:37.269 --> 00:33:40.430
And one of the tools that I used was developed
by Frederick Drove Brock.

00:33:40.430 --> 00:33:42.159
And I wanna stress that's it's only one of
many.

00:33:42.159 --> 00:33:46.149
But it was my absolute favorite was the "Brock
String" and that's the string you all have.

00:33:46.149 --> 00:33:47.340
Do you all have a--?

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:52.240
Well I have some others if there's somebody
here who needs one.

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:56.790
And there's more.

00:33:56.790 --> 00:33:58.960
[ pause ]

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:01.130
OK.

00:34:01.130 --> 00:34:04.420
So, here's what you do.

00:34:04.420 --> 00:34:10.510
Take the bead on the Brock String, which is
basically a household piece of string.

00:34:10.510 --> 00:34:13.690
And put it all the way to one end.

00:34:13.690 --> 00:34:15.690
The string should be about arm's length.

00:34:15.690 --> 00:34:23.290
Put the string up to the bridge of your nose
and look at the bead.

00:34:23.290 --> 00:34:27.860
And, hopefully you see one bead.

00:34:27.860 --> 00:34:30.630
But how many string images do you see?

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:33.610
&gt;&gt;male#7: Six.

00:34:33.610 --> 00:34:35.100
[ laughter ]

00:34:35.100 --> 00:34:39.160
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: How many string images?

00:34:39.160 --> 00:34:41.820
Do any of you see two string images?

00:34:41.820 --> 00:34:42.820
OK.

00:34:42.820 --> 00:34:45.320
Now take the bead and put it in the middle
of the string.

00:34:45.320 --> 00:34:50.380
For some of you it might be easier if the
bead is closer to your nose, some further

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:51.380
away.

00:34:51.380 --> 00:34:55.610
But put it at about the middle of the string.

00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:57.700
Look at the bead again.

00:34:57.700 --> 00:35:00.160
Hopefully again you see it as single.

00:35:00.160 --> 00:35:05.980
And now, tell me, do you see something that
looks like this?

00:35:05.980 --> 00:35:12.440
So, you see a bead in the middle of an "X"
configuration right?

00:35:12.440 --> 00:35:17.040
Where there are two images converging on the
bead and then two images diverging away from

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:18.860
it.

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:23.100
Well when I first began to do this exercise
I was overwhelmed.

00:35:23.100 --> 00:35:29.700
Because, this exercise told me where my two
yes were pointing in space.

00:35:29.700 --> 00:35:33.870
It told me the line of sight of the two eyes.

00:35:33.870 --> 00:35:37.610
I didn't know what eye I was using at any
one time.

00:35:37.610 --> 00:35:40.030
I didn't know how I used my eyes.

00:35:40.030 --> 00:35:45.470
I had to bring that information into conscious
awareness, in order to be able to change the

00:35:45.470 --> 00:35:47.300
way I moved my eyes.

00:35:47.300 --> 00:35:48.500
OK?

00:35:48.500 --> 00:35:51.400
And this exercise gave me that information.

00:35:51.400 --> 00:35:56.230
So, when you were looking at the bead, this
string image was actually the image coming

00:35:56.230 --> 00:35:57.580
from your right eye.

00:35:57.580 --> 00:35:59.730
And this was the image coming from your left.

00:35:59.730 --> 00:36:05.390
And when I started the procedure, The only
way I could get that double string image and

00:36:05.390 --> 00:36:09.850
the " X ", was if the bead, and this is very
common in somebody with my condition, infantile

00:36:09.850 --> 00:36:15.730
esotropia, the only way I could get the "X"
is if I put the bead practically up to my

00:36:15.730 --> 00:36:16.900
nose.

00:36:16.900 --> 00:36:19.230
Within an inch of my nose.

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:21.510
And then I could get the "X" image.

00:36:21.510 --> 00:36:27.170
And then I started gradually moving the bead
further away from me, getting that "X" image

00:36:27.170 --> 00:36:28.290
and keep going on.

00:36:28.290 --> 00:36:33.350
Sometimes I'd see only one image of the bead,
and one image of the string.

00:36:33.350 --> 00:36:34.350
What did that mean?

00:36:34.350 --> 00:36:36.080
I was suppressing one eye.

00:36:36.080 --> 00:36:39.900
Sometimes I saw both images of the string
but they werenít coming in at the bead.

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:44.520
So, I knew that I was turning on the input
from both eyes but they weren't aligned.

00:36:44.520 --> 00:36:50.860
Well with this feedback, so simple, yet so
elegant, I could learn how to point the two

00:36:50.860 --> 00:36:54.400
eyes at the same place in space at the same
time.

00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:58.050
And I didn't stop with a little string like
this.

00:36:58.050 --> 00:37:02.300
I ended up using an eleven foot string.

00:37:02.300 --> 00:37:10.670
And, with five beads along it and I would
look at the close bead and get the " X " and

00:37:10.670 --> 00:37:15.130
then look at the further bead, and the next
bead, and so on, and so on, and so on.

00:37:15.130 --> 00:37:22.020
And this way, training my eyes to bi-fixate
on different distances in space.

00:37:22.020 --> 00:37:27.520
And, I still do these exercises on a regular
basis while jumping on a trampoline.

00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:31.550
Or striding along on a NordicTrack, because
if I am going to be binocular I need to be

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:32.550
binocular.

00:37:32.550 --> 00:37:36.060
Not just when I am standing still, but when
I'm moving.

00:37:36.060 --> 00:37:37.370
OK?

00:37:37.370 --> 00:37:44.760
And I wanna tell you about the time- And I'm
remembering it was February 21st, 2002.

00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:48.040
I remember this day like it was yesterday.

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:53.630
When I was doing vision therapy at my developmental
optometristís office with a vision therapist,

00:37:53.630 --> 00:37:56.060
I did therapy for a year.

00:37:56.060 --> 00:37:58.120
One week for a year.

00:37:58.120 --> 00:37:59.120
Once a week for a year.

00:37:59.120 --> 00:38:01.260
And practiced at home every day.

00:38:01.260 --> 00:38:07.390
And the exercise was to look at a close bead,
and I had just gotten to a point where I could

00:38:07.390 --> 00:38:09.780
do that very well with a single bead.

00:38:09.780 --> 00:38:13.180
And now I graduated to using two beads.

00:38:13.180 --> 00:38:16.110
And the therapist said "OK, look at the close
bead."

00:38:16.110 --> 00:38:17.930
I said yep I got it, got the "X."

00:38:17.930 --> 00:38:20.580
Now, she said, "Look at the further bead."

00:38:20.580 --> 00:38:24.551
And I looked at her and said, ìYep, I got
the ëXíî "Now look at the close bead, now

00:38:24.551 --> 00:38:27.720
look at the further bead."

00:38:27.720 --> 00:38:32.570
And I said to her, ìI can feel my eyes movingî.

00:38:32.570 --> 00:38:35.420
I could feel them turning in to see the closer
bead.

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:38.220
I could feel them turning out together.

00:38:38.220 --> 00:38:40.400
In coordination to see the further bead.

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:42.600
I said to her, I feel my eyes moving.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:44.770
And, she said, "That's great.

00:38:44.770 --> 00:38:47.950
We'll do it a little longer then we'll move
on to another activity."

00:38:47.950 --> 00:38:50.140
I said to her, ìNo, I don't wanna stop.

00:38:50.140 --> 00:38:51.490
I just wanna keep doing this.

00:38:51.490 --> 00:38:54.300
I just want to feel the way this feels.

00:38:54.300 --> 00:38:58.830
I want to remember how this feels, so I can
use this, when I don't have a Brock String

00:38:58.830 --> 00:39:05.540
with me.î And, it was that afternoon, after
that vision therapy session, that I went out

00:39:05.540 --> 00:39:12.711
to my car and sat down in the driver seat;
and I looked at the steering wheel, and it

00:39:12.711 --> 00:39:15.900
was floating in front of the dashboard.

00:39:15.900 --> 00:39:20.970
With this palpable volume of space between
the steering wheel and the dashboard and I

00:39:20.970 --> 00:39:24.500
had never seen anything like that before.

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:29.330
And I thought to myself, could this be stereo
vision?

00:39:29.330 --> 00:39:30.330
And then I thought , no way.

00:39:30.330 --> 00:39:31.330
I'm a neuroscientist.

00:39:31.330 --> 00:39:34.950
I know what I teach in class.

00:39:34.950 --> 00:39:37.750
It was the day after my 48th birthday.

00:39:37.750 --> 00:39:43.060
I was more than 40 years past the critical
period for the development of stereopsis.

00:39:43.060 --> 00:39:44.720
This had to be something different.

00:39:44.720 --> 00:39:49.170
The sun was setting, and I thought, oh the
sun is casting the light into the car at an

00:39:49.170 --> 00:39:50.170
odd angle.

00:39:50.170 --> 00:39:52.190
And this must explain what is going on.

00:39:52.190 --> 00:39:53.300
[ laughter ]

00:39:53.300 --> 00:39:54.410
OK.

00:39:54.410 --> 00:40:00.400
But the next day I went out to my- I did my
vision therapy exercises in the morning, including

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:04.790
the Brock String, and I went to the car to
drive to work, and I went to address the rear

00:40:04.790 --> 00:40:09.420
view mirror, and it was floating in front
of the dashboard.

00:40:09.420 --> 00:40:12.050
And, all that day my vision began to change.

00:40:12.050 --> 00:40:13.720
And all that month.

00:40:13.720 --> 00:40:17.750
Well, there were many other vision therapy
exercises that I did.

00:40:17.750 --> 00:40:20.170
I'm not going to go through them here now.

00:40:20.170 --> 00:40:24.490
Because I just want to tell you, you can ask
me some more about them afterwards if you'd

00:40:24.490 --> 00:40:25.840
like.

00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:29.560
Because I just want to tell you what it's
like to first see the world when you can point

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:32.840
two eyes at the same place in space at the
same time.

00:40:32.840 --> 00:40:35.350
It was a remarkable change.

00:40:35.350 --> 00:40:37.560
One that I could never have predicted.

00:40:37.560 --> 00:40:42.370
That is certainly not in the textbooks where
they look at stereopsis as just a little frosting

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:44.460
on the cake when it comes to vision.

00:40:44.460 --> 00:40:46.910
It completely transformed the way I saw.

00:40:46.910 --> 00:40:50.050
So, take trees.

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:55.170
All of a sudden I could see- I always knew
that trees, the canopy of a tree was round,

00:40:55.170 --> 00:40:56.170
right?

00:40:56.170 --> 00:40:57.570
But I never saw it that way.

00:40:57.570 --> 00:41:02.150
To me a tree was like a kid's drawing, it
was just flat looking when you looked at it

00:41:02.150 --> 00:41:03.340
front on.

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:08.690
And now, all of a sudden, I could see how
the outer branches enclosed and captured whole

00:41:08.690 --> 00:41:12.560
volumes of space through which the inner branches
came through.

00:41:12.560 --> 00:41:15.940
It was just absolutely spectacular.

00:41:15.940 --> 00:41:18.240
Snowfall.

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:22.550
My first snowfall , David referred to that,
was just unbelievable.

00:41:22.550 --> 00:41:25.000
My first snowfall in stereo.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:30.860
Because I could see how each flake occupied
its own region of space, And there were these

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:34.070
palpable pockets of space between one flake
and another.

00:41:34.070 --> 00:41:39.090
And all together they produced a beautiful
three dimensional dance.

00:41:39.090 --> 00:41:45.100
One of the things I mention to people, because
it seems to- people seem to relate to this,

00:41:45.100 --> 00:41:46.760
with my view of a mirror.

00:41:46.760 --> 00:41:53.270
In the past when I looked at my reflection
in a mirror, my image was on the plane of

00:41:53.270 --> 00:41:55.061
the mirror, not behind it.

00:41:55.061 --> 00:41:56.930
It was on the plane of the mirror.

00:41:56.930 --> 00:42:01.471
So much so, if there was a speck of dirt on
the mirror, I thought it was on my clothes,

00:42:01.471 --> 00:42:04.310
and would try to wash it away.

00:42:04.310 --> 00:42:09.720
And I remember the day when I looked in a
mirror and my image was no longer on the plane

00:42:09.720 --> 00:42:12.870
of the mirror, but somewhere behind it.

00:42:12.870 --> 00:42:14.640
In reflected space.

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:18.630
And that's when I understood what " Lewis
Carol " meant when he titled one of his books,

00:42:18.630 --> 00:42:20.030
" Through The Looking Glass."

00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:26.820
When I look through a window now, instead
of having the image just sort of flattened

00:42:26.820 --> 00:42:28.100
onto the--.

00:42:28.100 --> 00:42:33.770
Within the frame of the window, I now see
it in three dimensions extending great distances

00:42:33.770 --> 00:42:35.700
beyond the window.

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:37.800
That was a real revelation.

00:42:37.800 --> 00:42:41.580
And I am still confused by reflection.

00:42:41.580 --> 00:42:45.810
Because if youíre sitting- One day I was
sitting in a restaurant, and it was Christmas

00:42:45.810 --> 00:42:51.610
time and I am sitting here, and to my left
on the opposing wall of the restaurant was

00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:52.870
a bunch of lights.

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:54.320
Christmas lights.

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:58.530
Which were reflected by the window onto the
street outside.

00:42:58.530 --> 00:43:04.220
And I looked outside and I saw the reflected
lights not on the plane of the window, but

00:43:04.220 --> 00:43:05.220
somewhere out there in space.

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:10.650
And I thought, why did they string Christmas
lights in the middle of the street.

00:43:10.650 --> 00:43:17.040
And then, of course I realized what was going
on, I'm totally captivated by the way reflections

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:22.290
have this three dimensional field to them
that I had never appreciated before.

00:43:22.290 --> 00:43:28.370
There were some surprising consequences of
seeing in 3D that went beyond just that the

00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:29.680
sense of depth.

00:43:29.680 --> 00:43:32.340
That sense of pockets of space between things.

00:43:32.340 --> 00:43:39.280
And that one was edges in objects perhaps
because now I could locate them so much more

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:40.280
precisely.

00:43:40.280 --> 00:43:45.380
Took on a sharpness and a definition that
I never seen before.

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:50.880
So take this painting for example, by Ingres
which is in the Metropolitan Museum of Art,

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:52.580
in New York.

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:56.490
And, take a look at the creases and folds
in the princess's gown.

00:43:56.490 --> 00:44:01.540
I used to look at a painting like that and
think, "Gosh it's gorgeous", but, nobody sees

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:02.540
that way.

00:44:02.540 --> 00:44:11.910
Nobody actually sees the crinkles and the
creases with such sharp definition.

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:16.800
And then, after my vision changed, yes indeed,
I did see them that way too.

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:22.940
So, edges and borders became much, much sharper.

00:44:22.940 --> 00:44:27.230
We have a way of understanding depth called,
motion parallax.

00:44:27.230 --> 00:44:33.970
Which means that as you move like this, back
and forth, images close to you appear to move

00:44:33.970 --> 00:44:36.060
at a faster rate than images further away.

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:39.930
And also, in an opposite direction of images
further away.

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:43.380
And that gives you a sense of depth that you
can see with one eye.

00:44:43.380 --> 00:44:49.540
But even that sense of depth was greatly enhanced
when I had this special quality of stereovision.

00:44:49.540 --> 00:44:53.260
The pockets of space between things.

00:44:53.260 --> 00:44:56.620
And my peripheral vision improved.

00:44:56.620 --> 00:44:57.980
How?

00:44:57.980 --> 00:45:01.560
My awareness of things in the visual periphery
improved.

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:02.560
Why?

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:05.730
Because when youíre cross-eyed your vision
is inefficient.

00:45:05.730 --> 00:45:09.360
You're looking with one eye and you have to
suppress the other.

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:14.310
And so, as a result, you take in less of the
visual world.

00:45:14.310 --> 00:45:18.581
Once I resolved the conflict between the two
eyes, because that's the major problem with

00:45:18.581 --> 00:45:19.850
strabismus , not lack of stereo.

00:45:19.850 --> 00:45:22.260
It's a visual conflict between the two eyes.

00:45:22.260 --> 00:45:26.960
Once I resolved that conflict, by pointing
the two eyes at the same spatial location

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:30.900
, then I could take in more of the visual
periphery.

00:45:30.900 --> 00:45:35.950
And so when I'm driving, I now notice that
there's a rear-view mirror off to my upper

00:45:35.950 --> 00:45:36.950
right.

00:45:36.950 --> 00:45:38.980
Which means that I tend to look at it more.

00:45:38.980 --> 00:45:41.970
which makes me a much better driver.

00:45:41.970 --> 00:45:49.190
And finally, I just want to add that many
people will say to you, "Oh, I understand

00:45:49.190 --> 00:45:50.740
what you're saying, it's all very cool.

00:45:50.740 --> 00:45:53.870
But if I do this, I close one eye, the world
doesn't look all that different.

00:45:53.870 --> 00:45:58.460
So I don't really understand why you think
it's so wonderful, this stereovision business."

00:45:58.460 --> 00:46:04.230
And, I puzzled about that for a long time,
until the day, about three years after my

00:46:04.230 --> 00:46:08.690
vision began to change, when I went to see
the last Star Wars movie.

00:46:08.690 --> 00:46:10.130
The Revenge of The Sith.

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:12.460
With my kids and my husband.

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:15.170
It was in 2005.

00:46:15.170 --> 00:46:19.870
And they insisted we go on midnight of the
opening night, and I was not in the least

00:46:19.870 --> 00:46:21.720
bit interested.

00:46:21.720 --> 00:46:24.710
Star Wars was OK, but not worth staying up
all night for.

00:46:24.710 --> 00:46:27.380
And being in a theater with screaming kids
and all of that.

00:46:27.380 --> 00:46:28.380
Right?

00:46:28.380 --> 00:46:31.180
But, my husband said this is a great family
activity.

00:46:31.180 --> 00:46:34.350
So off we went at midnight to see the movie.

00:46:34.350 --> 00:46:40.210
And I'm looking at the movie and I'm getting
this incredible sense of the spaceships moving

00:46:40.210 --> 00:46:41.210
through space.

00:46:41.210 --> 00:46:44.500
And volumes of space in the move, and all
this sort of stuff.

00:46:44.500 --> 00:46:52.740
And I thought, ìWow, cinematography has really
improved since the last Star Wars film.î

00:46:52.740 --> 00:46:56.330
And it was only until I had a good nightís
sleep that I realized that cinematography

00:46:56.330 --> 00:47:00.260
wasn't all that different between Star Wars
V and Star Wars VI.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:03.500
What had changed was my own visual perception.

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:10.470
That that sense of space and volume that I
saw in the movie was due to clever tricks

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:15.650
by the cinematographers using binocular depth
cues and motion cues, to evoke the sense of

00:47:15.650 --> 00:47:19.160
depth, to evoke a sense of space and volume.

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:23.860
But, I couldn't appreciate that deep sense
of space and volume which was suggested by

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:28.990
the movie until I had actually seen it in
real life.

00:47:28.990 --> 00:47:34.380
And so, when you just close one eye and you
look out on the world, you still have a lifetime

00:47:34.380 --> 00:47:38.800
of stereo experiences to fill in that missing
stereo information.

00:47:38.800 --> 00:47:40.510
But I never had that.

00:47:40.510 --> 00:47:46.970
And when I began to first see in stereo it
was a radically different experience.

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:52.080
And so, I'll just end by saying that some
of you may know, well, you probably don't

00:47:52.080 --> 00:47:53.080
know.

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:56.480
My husband between 1992 and 2005 was an astronaut.

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:58.580
He flew on the space shuttle three times.

00:47:58.580 --> 00:48:02.730
And his space launches were absolutely spectacular
experiences.

00:48:02.730 --> 00:48:08.080
This is a photo of his first launch in 1996,
it was a night launch.

00:48:08.080 --> 00:48:10.420
Incredible noise and lights and sounds.

00:48:10.420 --> 00:48:13.640
And you can feel the pressure waves of the
shuttle.

00:48:13.640 --> 00:48:15.540
Amazing experience.

00:48:15.540 --> 00:48:20.450
But, even that pales in comparison to first
seeing in stereo depth.

00:48:20.450 --> 00:48:21.450
So, thank you.

00:48:21.450 --> 00:48:22.450
[ applause ]

00:48:22.450 --> 00:48:23.450
More questions?

00:48:23.450 --> 00:48:30.400
&gt;&gt;male#8: So remind me the retina moves with
the eye right?

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:43.690
Like when you move the eye to look in different
directions, the retina moves along.

00:48:43.690 --> 00:48:44.690
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: Yes, it does.

