So, you were basically training both eyes.

00:50:23.420 --> 00:50:29.780
During the plastic period you did the right
things, as opposed to what most people do.

00:50:29.780 --> 00:50:31.770
You talked about they'd go fifteen degrees
off, put it on the blind spot, turn one eye

00:50:31.770 --> 00:50:35.450
off and then that eye just doesnít get trained.

00:50:35.450 --> 00:50:37.900
And that's why they never do recover.

00:50:37.900 --> 00:50:38.900
Is this-?

00:50:38.900 --> 00:50:41.540
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Well, yeah this makes absolute
sense.

00:50:41.540 --> 00:50:45.440
What you're talking about, where somebody
always uses the same eye for fixation, and

00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:52.060
always turns the other, causes the condition,
strabismic amblyopia.

00:50:52.060 --> 00:50:56.360
Which is sometimes commonly termed, "Lazy
Eye."

00:50:56.360 --> 00:51:01.670
But actually, there are several different
reasons why somebody can lose vision in one

00:51:01.670 --> 00:51:05.140
eye, which seems to be brain related.

00:51:05.140 --> 00:51:08.140
That is they didnít lose vision because there's
a problem with the eye itself.

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:12.270
The cornea, the lens, or something, or the
retina.

00:51:12.270 --> 00:51:15.710
And so what youíre talking about is a condition
called strabismic amblyopia.

00:51:15.710 --> 00:51:21.340
And youíre right, if you remain, if you alternate,
like I did, alternating strabismus.

00:51:21.340 --> 00:51:26.460
Then the acuity in both eyes stays relatively
good for both eyes.

00:51:26.460 --> 00:51:32.780
If you become, if you use only one eye for
fixation and turn in the other, become an

00:51:32.780 --> 00:51:35.210
amblyopic, then the acuity in one eye goes
way down.

00:51:35.210 --> 00:51:38.450
But it actually passed the critical period.

00:51:38.450 --> 00:51:43.560
That also can be greatly improved.

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:45.700
And you can get it back.

00:51:45.700 --> 00:51:48.140
I'm not saying it's easy, but you can.

00:51:48.140 --> 00:51:49.830
And there also these intriguing stories.

00:51:49.830 --> 00:51:53.400
I know one man, this happened to him.

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:59.760
Strabismic amblyopia like I just described,
then he lost vision in his good eye.

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:08.810
And, in a large percentage of cases where
that happens, vision in the amblyopic eye,

00:52:08.810 --> 00:52:14.220
which can be awful, can sometimes recover
all the way back up to twenty- twenty.

00:52:14.220 --> 00:52:18.970
So, it's as if the brain has suppressed that
input all these years.

00:52:18.970 --> 00:52:21.140
But, when forced to use it, it can come back.

00:52:21.140 --> 00:52:24.970
This doesn't happen in every case, but it
happens in enough of the cases to make one

00:52:24.970 --> 00:52:29.390
realize that, that eye is not completely unsalvageable.

00:52:29.390 --> 00:52:36.760
And now that scientists have embraced the
idea that vision can improve past the critical

00:52:36.760 --> 00:52:41.710
period, and maybe they can change the name
of the critical period to something less critical.

00:52:41.710 --> 00:52:42.710
[ laughter ]

00:52:42.710 --> 00:52:48.080
You know, call it a sensitive period, or the
period of maximum plasticity.

00:52:48.080 --> 00:52:52.600
Once people realize that there are studies
that are called "perceptual learning studies",

00:52:52.600 --> 00:52:58.900
and guess what they found, gee, you take a
person who has a weak eye, an amblyopia, and

00:52:58.900 --> 00:53:03.850
you do specific exercises with that eye it
improves.

00:53:03.850 --> 00:53:09.730
And so you can bring back the acuity, and
probably what's even more important, is teaching

00:53:09.730 --> 00:53:12.140
the person how to coordinate the two eyes
together.

00:53:12.140 --> 00:53:17.300
Because, if you don't do that, even if you
bring back acuity in the amblyopic eye, but

00:53:17.300 --> 00:53:21.710
the two eyes still aren't working together,
you are going to lose that acuity again.

00:53:21.710 --> 00:53:23.460
Cause you're not using it.

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:26.420
You have to teach the person how to use the
two eyes together.

00:53:26.420 --> 00:53:27.420
Yeah?

00:53:27.420 --> 00:53:31.310
&gt;&gt; female#1: What makes somebody one-eye-dominant?

00:53:31.310 --> 00:53:36.900
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Many of us, probably most
of us have an eye that is dominant.

00:53:36.900 --> 00:53:40.460
And, it's actually a very confusing topic.

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:44.160
So, for example, you may have one eye that
is dominant for certain viewing distances,

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:49.520
and the other eye dominant for other viewing
distances.

00:53:49.520 --> 00:53:57.270
So, it varies from person to person.

00:53:57.270 --> 00:54:02.220
And from condition to condition, which eye
may be dominant.

00:54:02.220 --> 00:54:06.641
You can all do this test, you can take your
arms and make a little window with them, like

00:54:06.641 --> 00:54:08.000
this.

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:10.580
And then look at a very distant object.

00:54:10.580 --> 00:54:13.970
Smallish object like the clock or something.

00:54:13.970 --> 00:54:17.080
And then close one eye, and then the other.

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:19.460
And the image should jump when you close one
of the eyes.

00:54:19.460 --> 00:54:20.902
And should not jump when you close the other.

00:54:20.902 --> 00:54:22.530
You have to look in the distance.

00:54:22.530 --> 00:54:25.760
Because what you're trying to do is make the
window so narrow, that basically only one

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:28.770
eye can look through it at any moment.

00:54:28.770 --> 00:54:30.540
Yeah.

00:54:30.540 --> 00:54:36.270
Then if you close one eye and the image jumps,
that means that was the dominant eye for that

00:54:36.270 --> 00:54:38.530
viewing distance.

00:54:38.530 --> 00:54:41.450
I don't know what makes an eye a dominant
eye.

00:54:41.450 --> 00:54:49.240
