00:54:56.050 --> 00:54:57.510
&gt;&gt;male#10: Does it work?

00:54:57.510 --> 00:54:58.960
It sounds so easy.

00:54:58.960 --> 00:54:59.960
[ laughter ]

00:54:59.960 --> 00:55:05.470
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: I would say there are better
approaches, but that is the standard of care.

00:55:05.470 --> 00:55:09.340
But, is not the best approach from everything
that I've seen.

00:55:09.340 --> 00:55:14.510
And the reason is this, that usually when
a child is suppressing one eye the problem

00:55:14.510 --> 00:55:16.910
is not the eye itself.

00:55:16.910 --> 00:55:18.720
The problem is with binocularity.

00:55:18.720 --> 00:55:20.660
They donít know how to use the two eyes together.

00:55:20.660 --> 00:55:25.490
Train them how to use the two eyes together
and they will use the two eyes together, and

00:55:25.490 --> 00:55:28.000
the acuity in that eye will get better.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:35.670
So, if you patch the good eye and you leave
the weak eye to do all the visual processing,

00:55:35.670 --> 00:55:36.870
you'll bring up its acuity.

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:44.070
But, then when you stop patching, at least
the records show, that about, I forget now,

00:55:44.070 --> 00:55:45.470
is it 30 percent?

00:55:45.470 --> 00:55:50.870
A good percentage of kids who's acuity has
gone up in the weak eye, lose that ability.

00:55:50.870 --> 00:55:51.870
And-.

00:55:51.870 --> 00:55:54.010
&gt;&gt;male#10: So it works but itís not guaranteed,
so itís not--

00:55:54.010 --> 00:55:55.010
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Right.

00:55:55.010 --> 00:55:56.060
Because you're not getting at the basic problem.

00:55:56.060 --> 00:55:59.600
The basic problem is binocular coordination
it's not the acuity of the eye alone.

00:55:59.600 --> 00:56:01.640
So, you've got to get the eyes to work in
a binocularly coordinated way.

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:02.640
To solve the problem.

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:03.640
Yeah?

00:56:03.640 --> 00:56:09.780
&gt;&gt;male#11: One vision therapist used Moro
Reflex training as part of the-.

00:56:09.780 --> 00:56:11.440
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Yeah.

00:56:11.440 --> 00:56:14.210
&gt;&gt;male#11: Can you comment on-?

00:56:14.210 --> 00:56:16.300
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Primitive reflexes?

00:56:16.300 --> 00:56:20.260
Yeah I can comment on it.

00:56:20.260 --> 00:56:22.190
So, hereís-.

00:56:22.190 --> 00:56:29.580
If you are like I was, an infantile esotrope,
it means that something went wrong in those

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:31.200
first months of life.

00:56:31.200 --> 00:56:34.890
Because, you didnít develop normal binocular
vision.

00:56:34.890 --> 00:56:39.960
So the, the question becomes, is just your
vision that was affected?

00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:49.290
Or, are there other probes you can use to
see if there are other neurological problems

00:56:49.290 --> 00:56:50.920
that went along with it?

00:56:50.920 --> 00:56:53.060
Subtle ones.

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:56.060
Obviously not as severe as, letís say, cerebral
palsy or something.

00:56:56.060 --> 00:56:57.500
But subtle ones.

00:56:57.500 --> 00:57:01.400
And sometimes when you start looking, you
look at what a primitive reflex is.

00:57:01.400 --> 00:57:04.700
The infant reflex like the Moro Reflex.

00:57:04.700 --> 00:57:08.370
These reflexes are prominent in babies.

00:57:08.370 --> 00:57:13.690
And then, when you grow up, they become in
the background.

00:57:13.690 --> 00:57:16.660
You don't use them anymore.

00:57:16.660 --> 00:57:22.320
And so, if you take a patient and you test
to see if they are still using primitive reflexes,

00:57:22.320 --> 00:57:25.780
then it may be an indication again that during
that developmental period, when binocular

00:57:25.780 --> 00:57:27.170
vision wasn't developing normally.

00:57:27.170 --> 00:57:31.570
There were other neurological things not developing
normally as well.

00:57:31.570 --> 00:57:40.110
And then, the thought might be, maybe if we
work on those reflexes as well as the vision,

00:57:40.110 --> 00:57:44.200
try to get better bilaterality to a person,
maybe that'll help.

00:57:44.200 --> 00:57:46.890
So, that's where I think that approach comes
from.

00:57:46.890 --> 00:57:49.170
It's an intriguing idea.

00:57:49.170 --> 00:57:50.170
Yeah?

