But, when he was on the bases, he could both
look at the picture and look elsewhere at

00:59:34.570 --> 00:59:35.790
the same time.

00:59:35.790 --> 00:59:39.079
He could diverge his eyes in that way with
his exotropia.

00:59:39.079 --> 00:59:40.079
[ laughter ]

00:59:40.079 --> 00:59:48.660
And thereby have a better view of the world
and steal those bases.

00:59:48.660 --> 00:59:55.140
So, there may be advantages to that way of
seeing.

00:59:55.140 --> 00:59:56.140
[ laughter ]

00:59:56.140 --> 01:00:00.780
&gt;&gt;male#12: No, I'm sometimes joking that if
I could get stereovision, I'm not sure I would

01:00:00.780 --> 01:00:01.780
want it.

01:00:01.780 --> 01:00:05.100
Because I have several aspects that the eyes
work better than--

01:00:05.100 --> 01:00:06.230
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: And that's--.

01:00:06.230 --> 01:00:07.230
Yeah.

01:00:07.230 --> 01:00:08.230
Yeah.

01:00:08.230 --> 01:00:09.230
&gt;&gt;male #12: than they would most people.

01:00:09.230 --> 01:00:10.230
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: Right.

01:00:10.230 --> 01:00:11.230
And yeah.

01:00:11.230 --> 01:00:14.050
So then, it really does become a question
of--.

01:00:14.050 --> 01:00:16.430
It's a trade-off.

01:00:16.430 --> 01:00:22.780
And to get the stereovision, even if you,
let's say, you'd have to work at it.

01:00:22.780 --> 01:00:28.790
But if you can do both and some can, they
can pull in their eyes and then let them go

01:00:28.790 --> 01:00:31.500
out, then it could work.

01:00:31.500 --> 01:00:35.450
But usually, if you're in that situation,
it takes more effort to pull in your eyes

01:00:35.450 --> 01:00:36.890
than normal.

01:00:36.890 --> 01:00:39.240
And so, it's more effort to see in 3D.

01:00:39.240 --> 01:00:40.240
&gt;&gt;male #12: Right.

01:00:40.240 --> 01:00:43.420
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: And so, you're less likely
to want to do it.

01:00:43.420 --> 01:00:44.420
Yeah.

01:00:44.420 --> 01:00:48.280
&gt;&gt;male #13: I understand there's these things
called saccades.

01:00:48.280 --> 01:00:49.750
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: Yeah.

01:00:49.750 --> 01:00:50.750
Rapid eye movement.

01:00:50.750 --> 01:00:53.300
&gt;&gt;male #13: I'm looking at that.

01:00:53.300 --> 01:00:56.650
I think I'm looking at the space shuttle there,
but what's really happening is my eyes are

01:00:56.650 --> 01:00:57.650
going, pop, pop, pop, pop, pop, pop, pop.

01:00:57.650 --> 01:00:58.650
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Right.

01:00:58.650 --> 01:01:02.170
&gt;&gt;male#13: 15 hundred milliseconds or so,
and they're probably, basically, filling up

01:01:02.170 --> 01:01:03.170
a poster board of evidence.

01:01:03.170 --> 01:01:05.140
Well anyway, my first question is, do those
saccades happen same time in both eyes?

01:01:05.140 --> 01:01:06.140
So they're eyes are popping together.

01:01:06.140 --> 01:01:10.920
And second, I was just wondering if in the
case of somebody with strabismus when theyíre

01:01:10.920 --> 01:01:11.920
young, that maybe that's not working.

01:01:11.920 --> 01:01:12.920
And is there any evidence?

01:01:12.920 --> 01:01:18.680
It would seem to me a very easy thing to measure.

01:01:18.680 --> 01:01:19.680
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Right.

01:01:19.680 --> 01:01:20.680
Right.

01:01:20.680 --> 01:01:21.680
&gt;male#13: Is it the case?

01:01:21.680 --> 01:01:29.670
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: Well, if you look at saccades,
saccades can be of two types.

01:01:29.670 --> 01:01:30.860
Conjugate or disconjugate.

01:01:30.860 --> 01:01:33.360
Conjugate would mean both eyes going in the
same direction at the same time.

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:35.130
So youíre watching a tennis match in both
eyes.

01:01:35.130 --> 01:01:37.930
Swivel to the right when the ball goes to
the right, and both eyes swivel to the left

01:01:37.930 --> 01:01:39.020
when the ball goes to the left.

01:01:39.020 --> 01:01:41.300
Right and left and right and left.

01:01:41.300 --> 01:01:42.350
That's a conjugate saccade.

01:01:42.350 --> 01:01:48.300
And I don't think there's any evidence to
indicate that that's not normal in somebody

01:01:48.300 --> 01:01:50.540
with strabismus.

01:01:50.540 --> 01:01:54.790
When you make a vergence movement, turning
in both eyes to see something close, or turning

01:01:54.790 --> 01:01:58.810
them out to see something further away.

01:01:58.810 --> 01:02:02.830
That actually takes much more time than a
rapid saccade.

01:02:02.830 --> 01:02:08.760
And by the way saccade are the very fastest
movements we can make, period.

01:02:08.760 --> 01:02:12.840
You know, conjugate saccade.

01:02:12.840 --> 01:02:17.770
So when youíre turning in your eyes or turning
them out, it takes more time.

01:02:17.770 --> 01:02:24.230
Those are also a kind of saccade and those
are not normal in somebody with strabismus.

01:02:24.230 --> 01:02:26.070
In fact, they may not be existent.

01:02:26.070 --> 01:02:27.140
Yeah.

01:02:27.140 --> 01:02:28.210
Yeah.

01:02:28.210 --> 01:02:30.140
And those are not normal.

01:02:30.140 --> 01:02:32.380
That's basically what I learned to train.

01:02:32.380 --> 01:02:36.660
My fusion ranges are wonderful, in terms of
what I can fuse.

01:02:36.660 --> 01:02:42.940
But, it does take me longer than average to
go from looking close to looking far.

01:02:42.940 --> 01:02:45.580
to make the vergance movements back and forth.

01:02:45.580 --> 01:02:48.280
So, still working on that.

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:49.280
One last question.

01:02:49.280 --> 01:02:54.870
&gt;&gt;female #2: So, I have pretty normal vision
except that I am near sighted.

01:02:54.870 --> 01:02:59.440
But, it's harder for me, and I think for most
