01:02:59.440 --> 01:03:00.440
&gt;&gt; Susan Barry: Mm-hmm.

01:03:00.440 --> 01:03:03.330
&gt;&gt;female#2: And possibly also at dawn , but
I'm also not as often awake at dawn.

01:03:03.330 --> 01:03:04.330
[ laughter ]

01:03:04.330 --> 01:03:07.370
&gt;&gt;female#2: So, I donít have as much data
on that one.

01:03:07.370 --> 01:03:08.810
But I was wondering why that is.

01:03:08.810 --> 01:03:12.710
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: I think because you add up
all the cues you use.

01:03:12.710 --> 01:03:15.980
And so, at dusk light is dimmer.

01:03:15.980 --> 01:03:19.690
They are all monocular cues to depth.

01:03:19.690 --> 01:03:21.150
Perspective, object occlusion.

01:03:21.150 --> 01:03:27.800
I know for example that, if my hand is blocking
my view of the video camera, I know my hand's

01:03:27.800 --> 01:03:29.250
in front of the video camera.

01:03:29.250 --> 01:03:30.340
Object occlusion.

01:03:30.340 --> 01:03:37.410
Perspective, motion parallax, shading and
shadows, give you a sense of roundness and

01:03:37.410 --> 01:03:38.410
depth.

01:03:38.410 --> 01:03:39.410
Those all come from one eye.

01:03:39.410 --> 01:03:44.170
And you combine those with your sense of stereo
depth to see.

01:03:44.170 --> 01:03:48.000
And so as those cues begin to fade because
the light is beginning to fade.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.220
Your depth perception is going to go down.

01:03:50.220 --> 01:03:52.990
&gt;&gt;female#2: It seems odd though that it's
actually better at night.

01:03:52.990 --> 01:03:55.590
&gt;&gt;Susan Barry: Your depth perception- you're
saying it's better at night.

01:03:55.590 --> 01:04:01.940
&gt;&gt;female#2: If I am playing tennis with my
